You are implementing E11-T2: Piano roll canvas renderer for a DAW project. Follow TDD - write tests first, then implement.

## Architecture Context

The project has an existing canvas renderer at `src/ui/arrangement/arrangement-renderer.ts` that you must follow as a pattern. It uses:
- Pure function `renderArrangement(rc: RenderContext)` - no DOM mutations
- Design tokens as const objects (COLOR, FONT_MONO, TEXT_XS, etc.)
- Helper functions like `secondsToX()`, `trackY()`, `hexToRgba()`
- DPI-aware rendering (handled by the panel component, not the renderer)
- Render stages: background → ruler → grid → lanes → headers → clips → playhead

## Data Types Available (from src/state/track/types.ts)

```typescript
type MIDINoteEvent = {
  readonly id: string;
  readonly pitch: number;    // 0-127
  readonly velocity: number; // 0-127
  readonly startTime: number; // seconds, relative to clip start
  readonly duration: number;  // seconds
};

type MidiClipModel = {
  readonly type: "midi";
  readonly id: string;
  readonly trackId: string;
  readonly startTime: number;
  readonly duration: number;
  readonly noteEvents: readonly MIDINoteEvent[];
  readonly name: string;
};
```

## What to create

### 1. `src/ui/piano-roll/piano-roll-renderer.ts`

Pure canvas renderer for the piano roll editor:

```typescript
// View state for the piano roll (independent from arrangement)
export type PianoRollViewState = {
  scrollX: number;        // seconds
  scrollY: number;        // MIDI note number at top (0-127, higher = higher pitch)
  pixelsPerSecond: number; // horizontal zoom
  noteHeight: number;     // pixels per semitone (12-20px recommended)
  keyboardWidth: number;  // width of piano keyboard sidebar (48px)
};

export type PianoRollTool = "pencil" | "select" | "erase";

export type PianoRollRenderContext = {
  ctx: CanvasRenderingContext2D;
  width: number;
  height: number;
  view: PianoRollViewState;
  notes: readonly MIDINoteEvent[];
  selectedNoteIds: readonly string[];
  cursorSeconds: number;
  bpm: number;
  clipStartTime: number;   // absolute timeline position of the clip
  clipDuration: number;
  tool: PianoRollTool;
  velocityLaneHeight: number; // height of velocity lane at bottom (60px)
};
```

Rendering stages:
1. `drawBackground(rc)` - dark background (#111111)
2. `drawNoteGrid(rc)` - horizontal lines for each pitch, alternating colors for white/black keys. White keys slightly lighter than black key rows.
3. `drawTimeGrid(rc)` - vertical beat/bar grid lines (same logic as arrangement grid)
4. `drawNotes(rc)` - Note rectangles: fill with blue (#0066ff) at 80% opacity, border 2px. Selected notes get white border. Position: x from note.startTime, width from note.duration, y from pitch (higher pitch = higher on screen). Use the standard neo-brutalist 2px borders.
5. `drawKeyboard(rc)` - Piano keyboard sidebar on the left. Draw white and black keys for the visible pitch range. Label C notes (C0, C1, ... C10).
6. `drawVelocityLane(rc)` - Bottom lane showing per-note velocity bars. Each bar's x matches its note, height proportional to velocity (0-127), colored blue.
7. `drawPlayhead(rc)` - Vertical red line at cursor position.
8. `drawRuler(rc)` - Time ruler at top (24px) with bar/beat labels.

Key helpers:
```typescript
export function secondsToX(seconds: number, view: PianoRollViewState): number {
  return view.keyboardWidth + (seconds - view.scrollX) * view.pixelsPerSecond;
}

export function pitchToY(pitch: number, view: PianoRollViewState, height: number, velocityLaneHeight: number): number {
  // Higher pitch = higher on screen (lower Y value)
  // scrollY is the MIDI note at the top of the viewport
  const visibleTop = view.scrollY;
  return RULER_HEIGHT + (visibleTop - pitch) * view.noteHeight;
}

export function isBlackKey(pitch: number): boolean {
  const pc = pitch % 12;
  return pc === 1 || pc === 3 || pc === 6 || pc === 8 || pc === 10;
}

export function noteName(pitch: number): string {
  const names = ["C", "C#", "D", "D#", "E", "F", "F#", "G", "G#", "A", "A#", "B"];
  const octave = Math.floor(pitch / 12) - 1;
  return names[pitch % 12] + octave;
}
```

### 2. `src/ui/piano-roll/piano-roll-renderer.test.ts`

Write tests FIRST covering:
- `isBlackKey()` correctly identifies black keys (C#, D#, F#, G#, A#)
- `isBlackKey()` correctly identifies white keys (C, D, E, F, G, A, B)
- `noteName()` returns correct names (noteName(60) === "C4", noteName(69) === "A4")
- `secondsToX()` converts seconds to pixels correctly
- `pitchToY()` converts pitch to Y coordinate correctly (higher pitch = lower Y)
- `renderPianoRoll()` calls all drawing stages without errors (test with a mock canvas context)
- `renderPianoRoll()` draws notes at correct positions
- `renderPianoRoll()` highlights selected notes differently
